images.alt: A massive, emerald-scaled dragon in a pristine hibachi chef’s uniform—white jacket stretched tight over its muscular frame, black apron singed at the edges—stands behind a gleaming steel grill in a bustling Japanese steakhouse. Its eyes burn with molten fury as it unleashes torrents of blazing orange and blue fire from its fanged maw, searing skewers of meats and vegetables mid-air. The flames curl and whip around the sizzling food, sending sparks and embers cascading across the room. Steam hisses up in great bursts as oils crackle on the grill, the aroma of charred delicacies filling the air.  The customers—wide-eyed and leaning back in their seats—shield themselves from the intense heat, napkins fluttering like flags in the fiery gusts. Wait staff freeze mid-step, their trays trembling, as the dragon’s tail swishes dangerously close to tables. Reflections of the inferno shimmer in the lacquered surfaces and sake glasses. Wisps of smoke coil toward the ceiling fans, partially obscuring paper lanterns swaying from the heat wave.  The entire scene is rendered in ultra-realistic, high-dynamic-range detail, with cinematic depth of field, every scale, droplet of sweat, and wisp of smoke sharply defined. Lighting shifts between the warm, flickering glow of the fire and the cool ambient restaurant lighting, creating a stark visual contrast. The perspective places the viewer at table height, as if part of the startled audience, capturing the raw chaos and heat of the moment.

A surreal, hyper-saturated portrait of a young man with curly dark hair, wearing oversized, circular orange-tinted sunglasses. The expression on his face is calm and confident, with a slightly pursed mouth and subtle stubble lining his jaw. His suit and tie are only partially visible, dissolving into a vortex of color. Explosions of vivid paint—yellows, oranges, magentas, and blues—radiate outward from his head, blending with splashes of texture that resemble brushstrokes and ink spills. The background is a soft, swirling off-white that contrasts sharply with the energetic chaos enveloping him. The entire composition evokes the feeling of a dream unraveling in slow motion, where identity merges with abstraction in a kaleidoscopic symphony.

record.text: That’s no Moon, er, Selectric https://hackaday.com/2025/08/12/thats-no-moon-er-selectric/ #Retrocomputing #typewriter #Selectric #Juki

external.description:
If you learned to type anytime in the mid-part of the 20th century, you probably either had or wanted an IBM Selectric. These were workhorses and changed typing by moving from typebars to a replaceable wheel. They were expensive, though worth it since many of them still work (including mine). But few of us could afford the $1,000 or more that these machines cost back in the day, especially when you consider that $1,000 was enough to buy a nice car for most of that time. [Tech Tangents] looks at something different: a clone Selectric from the sewing machine and printer company Juki.

The typewriter was the brainchild of [Thomas O’Reilly]. He sold typewriters and knew that a $500 compatible machine would sell. He took the prototype to Juki, which was manufacturing typewriters for Olivetti at the time.

Although other typewriters used typeballs, none of them were actual clones and didn’t take IBM typeballs. Juki even made their own typeballs. You’d think IBM might have been upset, but they were already moving towards the “wheelwriter,” which used a daisywheel element. Juki would later make a Xerox-compatible daisywheel printer, again at a fraction of the cost of the original.

Even the Juki manual was essentially a rip-off of the IBM Selectric manual. Sincerest form of flattery, indeed. It did appear that the ribbon was not a standard IBM cartridge. That makes them hard to find compared to Selectric ribbons, but they are nice since they have correction tape built in. The video mentions that you can find them on eBay and similar sites.

There were a few other cost savings. First, the Juki was narrower than most Selectrics. It also had a plastic case, although if you have ever had to carry a Selectric up a few flights of stairs, you might consider that a feature.

The Juki in the video doesn’t quite work, but it is a quirky machine with an odd history. Today, you can print your own typeballs. We wonder if these would be amenable to computer control like the Selectrics?
external.title: That’s No Moon, Er, Selectric
